in early European hours on Wednesday, consolidating just beneath Tuesday's session high of 163.31 after the pair posted its most decisive daily advance in several weeks. The daily chart presents a constructive picture: price has reclaimed ground lost during the sharp two-day pullback seen in early July and is now pressing into territory not visited since late June's brief spike above 162.67. The broader structure remains tilted in favour of the dollar.\n\nThe structural story over the past month is one of resilience. After the pair spent much of late June coiling in a narrow band around 161.75, a clean break higher on 30 June carried price to 162.67 before a sharp reversal on 2 July dragged it back towards 160.60 \u2014 a prior reaction zone that has now registered four distinct touches and has clearly acted as a meaningful floor. The subsequent recovery was methodical rather than impulsive, with price grinding back through the 161.30\u2013162.00 corridor across two weeks before Tuesday's push above 163.00 gave the bulls a more decisive foothold. The 162.40\u2013162.55 area, which capped multiple daily closes through mid-July, now functions as the nearest structural reference below current price; how price behaves on any pullback towards that band will be telling.\n\nOn the H1 chart, the intraday picture is one of orderly digestion. Following Tuesday's spike to 163.31, the pair pulled back to 162.84 within the same hour before recovering and settling into a tight range between roughly 163.00 and 163.18 through the overnight and early London session. Hourly candles are small-bodied and overlapping, consistent with consolidation rather than distribution. The 163.00 round-number level has attracted dip-buying interest on each test, and price has not yet threatened a meaningful break below it.\n\nOn the calendar, US Unemployment Claims at 08:30 UTC carries medium-impact status and represents the most significant scheduled risk of the session. A reading that surprises to the upside \u2014 suggesting labour market softening \u2014 could weigh on the dollar and introduce a sharper test of the 163.00 area or the 162.40\u2013162.55 structural band beneath. Conversely, a firm print would likely reinforce the current bullish tone. Later in the session, Japan's National Core CPI and Flash Manufacturing PMI arrive after 19:30 UTC; both are flagged as low-impact, though any upside surprise in inflation data could prompt yen-supportive positioning given the Bank of Japan's ongoing policy deliberations.\n\nThe bullish read would come under pressure on a sustained daily close back below 162.40, which would suggest the recent advance has stalled and that the mid-July consolidation range remains the operative frame. A break and close beneath 161.30 would materially weaken the case for further upside and bring the 160.60 prior reaction zone back into focus as a key structural reference.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}